%%TITLE
Differences in survival outcome between oropharyngeal and oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma in relation to HPV status.
%%ABSTRACT
This study examined the prognostic significance of human papillomavirus (HPV) in patients with oropharyngeal and oral cavity squamous cell carcinoma (SCC).Tissue microarrays were constructed from oropharyngeal and oral cavity SCC (nÂ =Â 143). The presence of functional HPV in tumour was determined by combined assessments of p16 immunohistochemistry and HPV inÂ situ hybridisation.Oropharyngeal SCC patients presented with more advanced disease in comparison with oral cavity SCC patients (PÂ =Â 0.001). HPV is present in 60% and 61% of oropharyngeal and oral cavity SCC patients, respectively. HPV-positive oropharyngeal SCC patients with advanced TNM stages displayed better overall and disease-free survival outcomes than HPV-negative patients (PÂ =Â 0.022 and 0.046, respectively). Such survival differences were not observed in oral cavity SCC.HPV is common in both oropharyngeal and oral cavity SCC and is associated with better survival outcome in oropharyngeal SCC but not in oral cavity SCC patients.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Ethics approval (HREC/13/LPOOL/449) was obtained from the south-western Sydney Local Health District Human Research Ethics Committee via the Centre for Oncology Education and Research Translation (CONCERT) Biobank, Australia/TCRC/3/02-03-2015. All experimental procedures were conducted in accordance with the Declaration of Helsinki.
Formalin-ﬁxed parafﬁn-embedded tissues
Oropharyngeal and oral cavity SCC patients with T1-4, N0-3, M0 diagnosed between 2000 and 2014 were identi- ﬁed from the database of the NSW Cancer Registry. Department of Anatomical Pathology databases, surgeon and hospital records were used to verify and input missing data as required. Retrieved data were validated by the treating clinicians. Patients with missing and/or incomplete follow-up and treatment records were excluded from the study. Patients were followed up for the occurrence of an event, which was deﬁned as recurrence in any form or death from any cause, for between 2 and 275 (median = 47) months after diagnosis. A total of 143 oropharyngeal (n = 48) and oral cavity (n = 95) SCC patients were included in the study. Formalin-ﬁxed parafﬁn-embedded (FFPE) primary tumours and their corresponding haema- toxylin- and eosin-stained (H&E) slides were obtained from the Department of Anatomical Pathology, Liverpool Hospi- tal, NSW, Australia.
Tissue microarrays (TMA) construction
H&E slides were examined by light microscopy and located regions of interest (ROI) including centre and periphery of the tumour, and lymph node metastases where applicable. Duplicate tissue cores from each ROI were removed from the FFPE tissue and inserted into a recipient parafﬁn block using MTA-1 manual tissue arrayer (Beecher Instruments, Sun Prairie, USA). TMA blocks were sectioned at 3 lm thickness and collected on Superfrost plus glass slides (Thermo Fisher Scientiﬁc, Waltham, MA, USA) prior to HPV detection.
HPV detection
HPV detection was achieved by combined assessment of p16 immunohistochemistry (IHC) and HPV in situ hybridi- sation (ISH).
p16 IHC was performed using Dako Autostainer Univer- sal Staining System (Dako, Glostrup, Denmark). TMA sections were deparafﬁnised in xylene and rehydrated through graded alcohol. Antigen retrieval was carried out using heated Bond Epitope Retrieval Solution 2 (Leica, Biosystems, Newcastle, UK) in a water bath set at a temperature just below boiling point (98°C) for 30 min. The sections were sequentially incubated with primary p16INK4a antibody (Cintec; Roche, Upper Bavaria, Ger- many) for 15 min and then Post Primary Block and NovoLink Polymer (Leica Mikrosysteme Vertrieb GmbH, Wetzlar, Germany), each incubated for 10 min. Then, endogenous peroxidase was quenched in all sections with 3% hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) for 5 min.
Diaminobenzidine Plus (Dako) was used as the colour chromogen and was incubated for 5 min. The sections were counterstained with Harris haematoxylin and Scott’s bluing reagent, dehydrated with alcohol and xylene and then mounted on 24 9 50 mm glass coverslips using automatic coverslippers (Dako). Normal tonsillar tissue sections were selected as positive control.
HPV ISH was performed on BenchMark ULTRA Autostainer (Ventana Medical Systems; Roche, Basel, Switzerland) using ISH/VIEW Blue Plus Detection Kit and INFORM HPV III Family 16 DNA probe (Ventana Medical Systems; Roche). TMA sections were counter- stained with Red Counterstain II (Ventana Medical Systems; Roche), air-dried and then mounted on coverslips.
The result slides were evaluated semiquantitatively by four independent pathologists. The scorers underwent a period of training with a multiheader microscope to ensure consistent and reliable interpretation. Using a test series of at least 36 tissue core sections, intra- and interobserver agreements were estimated using Kappa (j) and Spearman rho (q). Training was ended when the desired level of agreement, consistent over time, was achieved (j > 0.6 and q > 0.8). An average score was obtained from the duplicate cores of each tissue sample. Immunoreactivity in the nucleus and cytoplasm was individually graded. Intensity and distribution of the immunoreactivity were recorded. All researchers were blinded to clinical and other laboratory data. HPV-positive SCCs were determined by the presence of a functional HPV in tumour cells, which is indicated by the positivity of HPV ISH with p16 IHC staining. Tumour cells with positive p16 IHC staining but negative for HPV ISH were considered as HPV negative as the overexpression of p16 can be derived from other mechanisms than HPV infection (9). Tumour cells with positive HPV ISH but lack of p16 staining were also considered as HPV negative as it indicated the presence of non-functional HPV.
Statistical analyses
HPV status and clinicopathological characteristics for both SCC types were compared using a two-independent-sample t-test for the continuous variable age and chi-squared or Fisher’s exact tests for categorical variables. Multiple response variables were dichotomised where possible to assist the analyses.
Survival analyses were conducted for the outcomes of both overall and disease-free survival, with time to each outcome calculated from the date of diagnosis. An event was deﬁned as recurrence in any form or death from any cause, with only the ﬁrst event taken into account. Patients without events were censored at the date of last known follow-up. Unadjusted survival curves were obtained using Kaplan–Meier estimates using IBM SPSS Statistics soft- ware version 22.0 (IBM, New York, USA) and compared with Log-Rank test. Uni- and multivariate survival analysis using Cox proportional hazards models was used to estimate the hazard ratio of clinicopathological characteristics and HPV status in relation to both overall and disease-free survival in oropharyngeal and oral cavity SCCs separately. Results for all analyses were only considered to be statistically signiﬁcant if the associated P-value was <0.05.
